/-
UFT Formal Verification - Symmetry Breaking (Level 11)
========================================================

HOW THE UNIFIED GROUP BECOMES THE WORLD WE SEE

The universe at high energies has SO(10) symmetry.
At lower energies, this symmetry breaks in stages:

  SO(10) → SU(5) × U(1)_χ     [at ~10¹⁶ GeV]
  SU(5) → SU(3) × SU(2) × U(1)_Y  [at ~10¹⁵ GeV]
  SU(3) × SU(2) × U(1)_Y → SU(3) × U(1)_EM  [at ~246 GeV]

Each breaking is caused by a scalar field (Higgs) acquiring a
vacuum expectation value (VEV). The UNBROKEN subgroup is the
STABILIZER of the VEV — the subgroup that leaves it invariant.

This is pure algebra: given a group G acting on a vector space V,
and a specific vector v ∈ V, compute Stab(v) = {g ∈ G : g·v = v}.

We formalize each stage of breaking and verify the stabilizer
dimensions match the expected subgroups.

STAGE 1: SO(10) → SU(5) × U(1)
  Higgs in the adjoint 45 of SO(10).
  VEV proportional to the complex structure J = L_{16}+L_{27}+L_{38}+L_{49}+L_{5,10}.
  Stabilizer: elements commuting with J = u(5) = su(5) × u(1).
  Dimension: 45 → 24 + 1 = 25 (20 generators broken).
  THIS IS ALREADY PROVEN in su5_so10_embedding.lean!

STAGE 2: SU(5) → SU(3) × SU(2) × U(1)
  Higgs in the adjoint 24 of SU(5).
  VEV proportional to diag(2, 2, 2, -3, -3) (hypercharge direction).
  Stabilizer: elements commuting with Y = su(3) × su(2) × u(1).
  Dimension: 24 → 8 + 3 + 1 = 12 (12 leptoquark generators broken).
  THIS IS ALREADY PROVEN in georgi_glashow.lean!

STAGE 3: SU(2) × U(1) → U(1)_EM
  Higgs doublet ⟨φ⟩ = (0, v).
  Stabilizer: the electromagnetic U(1) generated by Q = T₃ + Y/2.
  Dimension: 3 + 1 → 1 (3 generators broken → W⁺, W⁻, Z⁰ massive).

This file formalizes Stage 3 (electroweak breaking) and collects
the dimension counts for all three stages.

References:
  - Weinberg, S. "A Model of Leptons" PRL 19 (1967)
  - Glashow, S. "Partial Symmetries of Weak Interactions" NP 22 (1961)
  - Higgs, P. "Broken Symmetries and the Masses of Gauge Bosons" PRL 13 (1964)
  - Georgi & Glashow, "Unity of All Elementary-Particle Forces" PRL 32 (1974)
